# The Easy Way: useContext

In function components, the `useContext` hook gives you the current context value.

```jsx
import React, { useContext } from 'react';
import { UserContext } from './context/UserContext';

function Profile() {
  const { user, setUser } = useContext(UserContext);

  if (!user) return <Text>Not logged in</Text>;
  return <Text>Welcome, {user.name}</Text>;
}
```

- `useContext` accepts a context object (returned from `createContext`).
- It returns the current value from the nearest matching `Provider` above in the tree.
- If no provider is found, it returns the default value passed to `createContext`.

Because we passed `setUser` in the value, we can update it from anywhere:

```jsx
function LoginButton() {
  const { setUser } = useContext(UserContext);

  const login = () => {
    setUser({ name: 'Alice' });
  };

  return <Button title="Login" onPress={login} />;
}
```

When `setUser` is called, all components consuming that context re‑render.
